		<description>Caliber: .280 British. 20-round detachable mag. Select-Fire.
		
A .280 caliber automatic rifle and evolution of FN's "Universal Carbine" series, rebranded as the "Carabines atomatiques de moyenne puissance" (CAMP). The highly configurable CAMP rifles were produced for British rifle trials conducted in 1950 and 1951, compared alongside other rifles such as the EM-2.\n\nDespite performing favorably, the CAMP was ultimately rejected in favor of the EM-2 for British military adoption. Some CAMP rifles were sent to countries such as France, Canada, and the US for their own tests, and while the rifle was satisfactory, no country selected it quickly, and thus the CAMP rifle would never be adopted in this configuration. Naturally, FN was not stopped from continuing to develop the rifle, and over the course of successive prototypes, future iterations would morph into the iconic FN FAL.\n\nThis rifle uses the heavy barrel configuration.</description>
